"\n## Problems\nLet $x$, $y$ and $z$ all exceed $1$ and let $w$ be a positive number such that $\\log_x w = 24$, $\\log_y w = 40$ and $\\log_{xyz} w = 12$. Find $\\log_z w$. Show that it is 060.\n\n## Informal proof\nThe [[logarithm]]ic notation doesn't tell us much, so we'll first convert everything to the equivalent exponential forms.\n\n$x^{24}=w$, $y^{40}=w$, and $(xyz)^{12}=w$. If we now convert everything to a power of $120$, it will be easy to isolate $z$ and $w$.\n\n$x^{120}=w^5$, $y^{120}=w^3$, and $(xyz)^{120}=w^{10}$.\n\nWith some substitution, we get $w^5w^3z^{120}=w^{10}$ and $\\log_zw=060$.\n\n## Formal statement\n```isabelle\ntheorem aime_1983_p1:\n  fixes x y z w :: nat\n  assumes ht : \"1 < x \\<and> 1 < y \\<and> 1 < z\"\n    and hw : \"0 \\<le> w\"\n    and h0 : \"ln w / ln x = 24\"\n    and h1 : \"ln w / ln y = 40\"\n    and h2 : \"ln w / ln (x * y * z) = 12\"\n  shows \"ln w / ln z = 60\"\n```\n\n## Structured informal proof\nStep 1: Convert the logarithmic equations to their exponential forms.\nStep 1.1: $x^{24} = w$\nStep 1.2: $y^{40} = w$\nStep 1.3: $(xyz)^{12} = w$\n\nStep 2: Raise each equation to the power of 5, 3, and 10 respectively to make the exponents comparable.\nStep 2.1: $x^{120} = w^5$\nStep 2.2: $y^{120} = w^3$\nStep 2.3: $(xyz)^{120} = w^{10}$\n\nStep 3: Substitute the expressions from Step 2 into the equation from Step 2.3.\nStep 3.1: $w^5 \\cdot w^3 \\cdot z^{120} = w^{10}$\n\nStep 4: Simplify the equation to isolate $z^{120}$.\nStep 4.1: $z^{120} = w^{2}$\n\nStep 5: Convert the equation back to logarithmic form to find $\\log_z w$.\nStep 5.1: $\\log_z w = 60$\n\n## Lemmas\n### Lemma 1\nA lemma showing that if $a = b^c$, then $\\log_b a = c$ would be useful in steps 1 and 5.\n\n### Code 1\n```isabelle\nlemma log_exponential_conversion:\n  fixes a b c :: real\n  assumes \"a = b^c\"\n  shows \"ln a / ln b = c\"\n  by (simp add: assms)\n```\n\n### Lemma 2\nA lemma showing that if $a^m = b^n$, then $a^{km} = b^{kn}$ for any $k$ would be useful in step 2.\n\n### Code 2\n```isabelle\nlemma power_equality:\n  fixes a b m n k :: real\n  assumes \"a^m = b^n\"\n  shows \"a^(k*m) = b^(k*n)\"\n  by (simp add: assms)\n```\n\n### Lemma 3\nA lemma showing that if $a \\cdot b = c$, then $a = c / b$ would be useful in step 4.\n\n### Code 3\n```isabelle\nlemma multiplication_division_conversion:\n  fixes a b c :: real\n  assumes \"a * b = c\"\n  shows \"a = c / b\"\n  by (simp add: assms)\n```\n\nThese lemmas and the structured proof should help in formalizing the proof in Isabelle."